<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-01-23T19:53:25-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-01-23T19:53:25-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7256&amp;p=73061#p73061</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7256&amp;p=73061#p73061"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Decapping the PPU: worth it?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7256&amp;p=73061#p73061"><![CDATA[
A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netlist" class="postlink">netlist</a> is a low-level description of all the gates in a circuit and how they are connected, written in a simple HDL that resembles Boolean algebra. One might construct this by decapping a mapper, taking a photomicrograph, and identifying gates. (Lately, Quietust has been <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php?limit=50&amp;tagfilter=&amp;title=Special%3AContributions&amp;contribs=user&amp;target=Quietust&amp;namespace=&amp;year=2011&amp;month=1" class="postlink">reading the PPU and APU photos</a> to discover not-yet-documented behaviors, but at a higher level than netlists.) The resulting netlist can be synthesized into a CPLD, FPGA, or ASIC, allowing accurate clones of more complex mappers like MMC3, RAMBO-1, FME-7, later VRCs, and MMC5.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sun Jan 23, 2011 7:53 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
